data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has three Thread.Abort-related APIs that **throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8**:

| API Found | Location | Pattern |
|-----------|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | ThreadAbortException as control flow |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | ResetAbort to continue execution |

### Why it breaks

In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime **cannot** forcibly inject a `ThreadAbortException`. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation** where the code voluntarily checks a `CancellationToken`.

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — moved from ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop; replaces Thread.ResetAbort + finally flow
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        _cts.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

### Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of forced exception injection |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | New exception type for cancellation; `when` guard prevents catching unrelated OCEs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | No abort to reset — just exit the loop normally |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))` | Actually waits for the thread instead of sleeping blindly |
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; `volatile bool` cannot wake a blocked thread |

---

### Critical Pitfall: Blocking Calls

Your `GetNextItem()` comment says "may block." **This is the most important part.** A `CancellationToken` cannot interrupt a blocking call that doesn't know about it. You **must** thread the token through:

```csharp
// ❌ Won't respond to cancellation while blocked
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks indefinitely
}

// ✅ Wakes up immediately when token is cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` uses `Thread.Sleep`, replace it:
```csharp
// ❌ Not cancellable
Thread.Sleep(5000);

// ✅ Cancellable
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000); // returns early if cancelled
```

### Other Pitfalls

1. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — it's `IDisposable`; leaking it leaks timers/callbacks.
2. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — let it propagate except at the top-level loop where you decide to stop.
3. **Cancellation is not instant** — it only fires at the next checkpoint. If `ProcessItem` is long-running, add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` calls inside it at regular intervals.
4. **Pass the token through the full call chain** — if any method in the chain ignores it, cancellation stalls at that point.
